resampling analysis. It satisfies the \code{"starting trees"} dependency
declared by \link{ResamplingCommand} and \link{RatchetCommand}.
}
\details{
\subsection{Input format}{

The \verb{$trees} field accepts either a single \code{phylo} object or a
\code{multiPhylo} object. Node labels and branch lengths are stripped
automatically, as TNT does not use them.
}

\subsection{Command output}{

\verb{$render()} produces a multi-line \code{tread} block containing the trees
in TNT format.
}

\subsection{Queue integration}{

Calling \verb{$enqueue()} adds this command to a \link{CommandQueue} at priority
\code{230}.
}

\subsection{Inline rendering}{

\code{ReadTreesCommand} sets \verb{$inline} to \code{TRUE} by default. When used
within \code{\link[=execute_analysis]{execute_analysis()}}, the tree data is written to a separate
temporary file and a \verb{proc <filename>;} call is substituted in the TNT
script, preventing very large tree blocks from making the script
unreadable.
}
}
